      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25/4/88. ¶ MS is stamped:Royal Gardens Kew 4-Jun. 88. ¶  ¶ This day, dear Sir Joseph, a trading horticulturist here sent me a flowering Dendrobium Sumneri, which gave me an opportunity of verifying th...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">88.04.25</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1882-90, ff. 248-9.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">25/4/88.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">MS is stamped:</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Royal Gardens Kew 4-Jun. 88.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This day, dear Sir Joseph, a trading horticulturist here sent me a flowering Dendrobium Sumneri, which gave me an opportunity of verifying the original description from a fresh living plant, and at the same time to settle, that your suspicion of D. Phalaenopsis being identical with D. Sumneri, was well founded.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. Hooker to M, 15 August 1884 (in this edition as 84-08-15b), in reply to M to J Hooker, 25 June 1884 (in this edition as 84-06-25a).<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Indeed the two cannot even be separated as varieties. What you caused to be depicted in the bot. Magazine 6817<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hooker (1865–1904), vol. 111, t. 6817.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>is merely somewhat larger, though perhaps through cultured luxuriancy.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Will you kindly let Prof Dyer know this, so that the first name for this plant may be given to it also in the Kew Orchid House. Since I left the Garden I have very rarely opportunities to extend my researches to cultivated ornamental plants.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I had a kind letter from you last week,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. Hooker to M, 4 March 1888.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>concerning the labor involved in rearranging the genera of many great orders, an achievement,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">I</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>know to appreciate. Indeed if you never had done anything else than writing your share of the "genera",<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>it would immortalize you! Remarkably enough, intervals of about 40 years were between all the great "genera plantarum", which Tournefort, Linnaeus, Jussieu, Endlicher and finally you and Bentham wrote. It is now nearly 30 years since you took up the genera. I am sure we all wish, you could crown your labours with a new edition of that great opus, embracing all the discoveries of the three last decades. — You allude kindly to the Royal Society having had brought under its cognizance, what I may have accomplished here; all I can say is, that I honestly<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">did</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>what I<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">could</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>in a new distant land, and as I have<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">neither</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">property</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">nor family,</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I should regard any recognition from the great Royal Society now so late in my life all the more.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See also M to P. Sclater, December 1887.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>M was awarded one of the Royal Society's two Royal Medals for 1888.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>this is the first centennial Jubilee year for Australia too!<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn6" n="7">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>i.e. the centenary of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>British settlement in Australia: ‘this is … Australia too!’ is a marginal note with the intended position indicated by an asterisk.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Lady Hooker sent me kindly an impression of your admirable speech given on the occasion, when you received the Societys<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">highest</hi>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>bestowal.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn7" n="8">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hooker received the Royal Society's Copley Medal at the Society's Anniversary Meeting on 30 November 1887.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Perhaps you and Lady Hooker will at the end of the summer be down in some part of the coast, and her Ladyship may help you to look for Cheno[le]a Hirsuta. As I found it on the Schleswig coast, nearly half a century ago, directly opposite the British, [often] in a glabrous form among Suaeda, you are sure to discover it also there, though the W. coast may be still more promising for finding it.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn8" n="9">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The postscripts are written in the side and central margins of the letter.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Mr Fitzgerald illustrated D. Smillieae &amp; Sarcochilus<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Hartmanni<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn9" n="10">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>S. hartmannii?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>also under new names, though well known in cultivation.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn10" n="11">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">D. Smillieae</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>as<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Coelandria smillieae</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(R.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Fitzgerald<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(1875-94),<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>vol .1<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>part<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>7, plate<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>[2]), and<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>described<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Sarcochilus Hartmanni</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>as<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Sarcochilus rubricentrum<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>(R.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Fitzgerald<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(1880))<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and illustrated it in<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>R.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Fitzgerald (1875-94), vol. 2, plate [3].</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>When the "Key"<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn11" n="12">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B88.11.02.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>shall be through the press, I shall come to the naming of Papuan plants again, and then make up a set for Kew.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Towards autumn the sometimes spiral twist of the Chenolea is most marked; the axillary minute tufts of hairs lead also to distinguishing it from Suaeda maritima, &amp; of course the fruit altho' minute</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Chenolea Hirsuta</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Dendrobium Phalaenopsis</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Dendrobium Smillieae</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Dendrobium Sumneri</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Sarcochilus<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Hartmanni</p>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Suaeda maritima</p>
         </div>
      </body>
